/*
:name: latch_master_slave
:type: equiv
:verilog_top: latch_master_slave.ms8
:pyrope_top: ms8
*/

// LIVE equiv test (promoted 2026-07-20, todo/livehd/2f-latch) — THE KEY
// COMMIT-CLASS SHAPE. A master/slave pair on OPPOSITE phases IS a positive-edge
// flop. The golden is written as the latch pair (not as a flop) so the pair
// itself is what gets proven; a latch-pair-vs-FLOP golden would be the stronger
// downstream claim (2f-latch M4, native encoder).
//
// Why this shape matters under the no-time-borrowing scope ruling: the two
// latches are never SIMULTANEOUSLY transparent, so each one is soundly modeled
// as a flop-with-enable committing at the CLOSING edge of its window (master
// transparent-low -> commits at RISE; slave transparent-high -> commits at
// FALL), and the pair reconstructs ONE-cycle flop latency from commit classes
// alone. The one-cycle-latency claim is tested by the SIM fixture
// tests/fixme/latch_sim_master_slave.prp (2f-latch M5) — sim today emits
// nothing for a Latch; a naive "latch = flop" model without commit classes
// would give 2 cycles instead of 1, silently. Neither fix may model
// transparency — opposite-phase commit classes are what make it correct.
pub mod ms8(clk:bool, d:u8) -> (q:u8@[0]) {
  reg m:u8:[latch=true]
  reg s:u8:[latch=true]
  if !clk { m = d }
  if clk  { s = m }
  q = s
}
